# DBP corridor lateral calibration v1.0

At the terminal sheet `rho=-sqrt(1+sigma^2)`, write the upper return stem as

```text
sigma(h)=1+h(-1/2+i),       0<h<=1.
```

Here `Re(sigma)=1-h/2>0` and `Im(sigma)=h>0`.  Therefore

```text
Im(1+sigma^2)=2 Re(sigma) Im(sigma)>0.
```

The principal square root consequently has positive imaginary part.  The
continued terminal sheet is its negative, so `Im(rho)<0`.  Since

```text
m = 1/2 - 1/(2rho),
```

and `Im(1/rho)=-Im(rho)/|rho|^2>0`, it follows exactly that
`Im(m)<0`.  Complex conjugation gives `Im(m)>0` along the lower return stem
`sigma(h)=1+h(-1/2-i)`.  Thus the explicit rational calibration interval is

```text
h_0=1,   0<h<=h_0.
```

This algebraic sign argument is stronger than a first-order expansion and has
no unquantified remainder.  It confirms the Stage-3 convention:

```text
upper: Im(m)<0  selects delta_-^up
lower: Im(m)>0  selects delta_-^down.
```

The local pole coordinate is consistent because
`u_p=1/n=(2m-1)/m^2` and `du_p/dm=2(1-m)/m^3` is positive real at the dual
endpoint.  The established meridian relation is not modified.
